Image segmentation

In image segmentation, instead of assigning a class to a whole image as in image classification, we want to classify each pixel of an image. Let’s load the CamVid segmentation dataset using loadtaskdata to look at the data:

using FastAI
using FastAI.Datasets
using CairoMakie; CairoMakie.activate!(type="png")
using Metalhead
taskdata = Datasets.loadtaskdata(Datasets.datasetpath("camvid_tiny"), FastAI.ImageSegmentationTask);
image = getobs(taskdata, 1).input

Every pixel in this image is assigned one of the following classes:

classes = Datasets.getclassessegmentation("camvid_tiny")
32-element Vector{String}:
 "Animal"
 "Archway"
 "Bicyclist"
 "Bridge"
 "Building"
 "Car"
 "CartLuggagePram"

 "LaneMkgsNonDriv"
 "Misc_Text"

 "SignSymbol"
 "Sky"
 "SUVPickupTruck"
 "TrafficCone"
 "TrafficLight"
 "Train"
 "Tree"
 "Truck_Bus"
 "Tunnel"
 "VegetationMisc"
 "Void"
 "Wall"

ImageSegmentation is the learning method for this task. We can pass it the classes and an input image size a model will be trained on. As always, you can click on a symbol to look up its documentation and find out about other, optional, arguments.

method = ImageSegmentation(classes, (96, 128))
ImageSegmentation{2}(
    classes = ["Animal", "Archway", "Bicyclist", "Bridge", "Buil…], 
    downscale = 0, 
    projections = ProjectiveTransforms{2}(sz=(96, 128), buffered=true, augmentations=DataAugmentation.Identity()), 
    imageprepocessing = ImagePreprocessing(C=ColorTypes.RGB{FixedPointNumbers.N0f8}, T=Float32, buffered=true)
)

With a method and taskdata, the only thing we need before we can create a Learner is a backbone architecture to build the segmentation model from. We’ll use a pretrained model from Metalhead.jl (see the setup instructions), but you can use any convolutional architecture and a suitable model will be constructed from it (see UNetDynamic).

using Metalhead
backbone = Metalhead.resnet50(pretrain=true)[1:end-3]
learner = methodlearner(method, taskdata, backbone, ToGPU())
Learner()

We can grab a batch of data and visualize it. Here every color in the target mask represents a different class.

xs, ys = first(learner.data.training)
FastAI.plotbatch(method, xs, ys)

Now let’s finetune the model:

finetune!(learner, 10, 0.1)

Learner()

And look at the results on a batch of validation data:

xs, ys = first(learner.data.validation);
ŷs = learner.model(gpu(xs)) |> cpu;
FastAI.plotpredictions!(Figure(resolution=(1000, 3000)), method, xs, ŷs, ys)
